{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599286"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:52:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:52:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15540"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15540"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.74,0.15,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8231"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62920"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8231"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15540"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48371"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"6976"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20514"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62920"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman undergoes an abdominal computed tomography scan for investigation of chronic upper abdominal pain. The radiologist provides comments on the pancreas and its adjacent tissues and describes a hook-shaped structure that curves posteriorly and medially behind the superior mesenteric vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following anatomical structures is being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Accessory pancreatic duct","Cystic duct","Uncinate process","Main pancreatic duct","Hepatopancreatic ampulla"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccessory pancreatic duct\u003C/strong\u003E (duct of Santorini) is a smaller secondary pancreatic duct that typically drains into the duodenum separately from the main pancreatic duct. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecystic duct\u003C/strong\u003E connects the gallbladder to the common bile duct. The \u003Cstrong\u003Euncinate process\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer as it is a hook-like projection from the head of the pancreas that wraps around the superior mesenteric vessels. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emain pancreatic duct\u003C/strong\u003E (duct of Wirsung) is the primary drainage duct of the pancreas that joins with the common bile duct. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatopancreatic ampulla\u003C/strong\u003E (ampulla of Vater) is where the main pancreatic duct and common bile duct join before entering the duodenum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The uncinate process is a hook-like projection from the head of the pancreas that wraps around the superior mesenteric vessels.","The uncinate process is embryologically derived from the ventral pancreatic bud."],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Functional anatomy of the uncinate process and its role in endoscopic sinus surgery. Indian J Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2001 Jan;53(1):27-31. doi: 10.1007/BF02910975. PMID: 23119747; PMCID: PMC3450881."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48371"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15540"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48371"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T11:56:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T11:57:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8231"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62920"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationsh